{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/circuit-breakers/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 700px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/885fa6e310cdd07883ff4e836a5f95a8/782ec/circuit_breaker.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.42857142857143%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Circuit Breaker\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/885fa6e310cdd07883ff4e836a5f95a8/39600/circuit_breaker.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/885fa6e310cdd07883ff4e836a5f95a8/1aaec/circuit_breaker.png 175w,\n/static/885fa6e310cdd07883ff4e836a5f95a8/98287/circuit_breaker.png 350w,\n/static/885fa6e310cdd07883ff4e836a5f95a8/39600/circuit_breaker.png 700w,\n/static/885fa6e310cdd07883ff4e836a5f95a8/782ec/circuit_breaker.png 927w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>One of the most helpful patterns I've used in back end systems is the circuit breaker.</p>\n<p>Circuit Breakers are a resilience pattern - they stop your app from calling something that's already failing, like a third party API or an internal service.</p>\n<p>Here's how they work:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wrap your call and a circuit breaker.</li>\n<li>If errors spike, say 5 out of 10 requests, it trips and blocks future calls for a while.</li>\n<li>During that time, instead of spamming the broken system, it fails faster &#x26; returns a fallback.</li>\n<li>After a timeout, the breaker goes into a half open state. This lets a few requests through to test the waters. If they succeed, the breaker closes, but if not it trips again.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This helps prevent cascading failures, reduces pressure on fragile services, and gives them time to recover.</p>\n<p>If you've ever seen a system thrashing because retries kept hammering broken API, that's what circuit Breakers are designed to stop.</p>\n<p>Look up a circuit breaker library in your language and start using them!</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/john-pratt787/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Follow me</a> for more dev tips.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"The \"Circuit Breaker\" Design Pattern","draft":false,"description":"a","date":"2025-06-06","slug":"/circuit-breakers","tags":["design-patterns","software-dev","resiliency"]}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/circuit-breakers"}},"staticQueryHashes":["1466254954","2744132034","2759103021","3539500889"],"slicesMap":{}}